SIMPLE: ordinance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ordinance
<hw>Or"di*nance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>ordenance</ets>, OF. <ets>ordenance</ets>, F.
<ets>ordonnance</ets>. See <er>Ordain</er>, and cf. <er>Ordnance</er>,
<er>Ordonnance</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Orderly arrangement; preparation; provision.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They had made their <qex>ordinance</qex>⟦br⟧
Of victual, and of other purveyance.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rule established by authority; a permanent rule of
action; a statute, law, regulation, rescript, or accepted usage; an
edict or decree; esp., a local law enacted by a municipal government;
<as>as, a municipal <ex>ordinance</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou wilt die by God's just <qex>ordinance</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By custom and the <qex>ordinance</qex> of times.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Walking in all the commandments and <qex>ordinances</qex> of the
Lord blameless.</q> <rj><qau>Luke i. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Acts of Parliament are sometimes called
<xex>ordinances</xex>; also, certain colonial laws and certain acts of
Congress under Confederation; as, the <xex>ordinance</xex> of 1787 for
the government of the territory of the United States northwest of the
Ohio River; the colonial <xex>ordinance</xex> of 1641, or 1647. This
word is often used in Scripture in the sense of a law or statute of
sovereign power. <au>Ex. xv. 25.</au> <au>Num. x. 8.</au> <au>Ezra iii.
10.</au> Its most frequent application now in the United States is to
laws and regulations of municipal corporations. <au>Wharton (Law
Dict.).</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>An established rite or
ceremony.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Rank; order; station.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Ordnance</er>.]</ety> <def>Ordnance;
cannon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ordinand</ent>⟦br⟧
